@page "/faq"

<section class="faq-hero">
    <h1>Frequently Asked Questions</h1>
    <p>
        Have questions about Ripple, aquaponics, volunteering, or how our system works?
        You’re in the right place.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="faq-section">
    <h2>General Questions</h2>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What is Ripple?</h3>
        <p>
            Ripple is a community‑driven aquaponics initiative working to reduce food insecurity
            in the Chicagoland area through sustainable, year‑round food production.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What is aquaponics?</h3>
        <p>
            Aquaponics grows fish and plants together in a closed‑loop system. Fish produce nutrients
            for the plants, and the plants clean the water for the fish.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="faq-section">
    <h2>Food & Distribution</h2>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Is the food free?</h3>
        <p>
            Yes. Our produce and fish are distributed through local food pantries, shelters,
            and community partners at no cost to families.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What kinds of food do you grow?</h3>
        <p>
            We grow buttercrisp lettuce and other leafy greens, along with Nile tilapia — a hardy,
            nutritious freshwater fish.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Where does the food go?</h3>
        <p>
            We work with Chicagoland food pantries and community organizations to distribute food
            directly to neighborhoods facing food insecurity.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="faq-section">
    <h2>Facility & Safety</h2>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Is the facility safe and clean?</h3>
        <p>
            Absolutely. We use strict biosecurity practices, daily water testing, and separate zones
            for fish, plants, and packaging to ensure food safety.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Do you use chemicals or pesticides?</h3>
        <p>
            No. Aquaponics relies on natural nutrient cycles, beneficial bacteria, and clean water —
            not chemical fertilizers or pesticides.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Can I tour the facility?</h3>
        <p>
            Yes! We offer guided tours and educational workshops. Check our Get Involved page for
            upcoming opportunities.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="faq-section">
    <h2>Volunteering & Education</h2>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Do I need experience to volunteer?</h3>
        <p>
            No experience needed — we’ll teach you everything. Volunteers help with planting,
            harvesting, packaging, cleaning, and outreach.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Can students or researchers work with Ripple?</h3>
        <p>
            Yes. We welcome collaboration with students, educators, and researchers interested in
            sustainability, biology, engineering, or community impact.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Do you offer workshops?</h3>
        <p>
            Yes. We host workshops on aquaponics, sustainability, and community food systems.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="faq-section">
    <h2>Support & Donations</h2>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How can I support Ripple?</h3>
        <p>
            You can volunteer, attend workshops, partner with us, or donate to help expand our impact.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Are donations tax‑deductible?</h3>
        <p>
            Ripple is in the process of registering as a 501(c)(3) nonprofit. Once approved, donations
            will be tax‑deductible.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>
